<DocsLayout title="CLI Reference" description="lean-ctx command-line interface for MCP server, shell hook, and interactive mode.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx is a single Rust binary that operates in multiple modes depending on the command-line flags.
  </p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx [command] [options]</code></pre>

  <h2>Modes</h2>

  <h3>MCP Server (default)</h3>
  <p>Starts the MCP server via stdio. This is the mode used by editors like Cursor, Claude Code, Copilot, and Windsurf.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>Shell Hook</h3>
  <p>Execute a command and compress the output before printing:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx -c git status
lean-ctx exec cargo build</code></pre>
  <p>Ideal for shell aliases:</p>
  <pre><code>alias git='lean-ctx -c git'
alias cargo='lean-ctx -c cargo'</code></pre>

  <h3>Interactive Shell</h3>
  <p>Launch a shell wrapper that compresses all command output:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --shell
lean-ctx shell</code></pre>
  <p>This starts a <code>lean-ctx></code> REPL that passes commands to the system shell and compresses output.</p>

  <h3>Version</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --version</code></pre>

  <h3>Help</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --help</code></pre>

  <h2>Exit Codes</h2>
  <p>
    In shell hook mode (<code>-c</code>), lean-ctx forwards the exit code of the wrapped command.
    This ensures scripts and CI pipelines work correctly.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
